post_text: From Robinson teacher Christina Ibrahim: ‚ÄúWeather Balloons: Why not end this crazy year on a high note? Like really high, around 30,000 feet? That‚Äôs what our 5th graders did. They reviewed what they knew about earth‚Äôs atmosphere and the jet stream, learned how ham radios and APRS.fi work, and then used real live data to graph altitude points. Science and Math, best friends ever. Oh and as the balloons raced across the continent so Social Studies got to poke in as well. Some Robinson students have been asked to participate in presenting a paper at the ARISS national laboratory virtual conference. Joanne Michael, former Meadows teacher, will be co-writing the paper with them, but these kids are going to be professionally published 6th graders next year. Pretty cool stuff.‚Äù Check it out ... https://www.nasa.gov/directorates/heo/scan/communications/outreach/balloon_racing_hams

post_text: Brian Neitz, a MBUSD alumni & parent, was diagnosed with leukemia on June 17, 2019 during a routine physical. Other than fatigue, he did not have any other symptoms. He has completed induction chemo and needs a bone marrow transplant. Currently a match has not been found. He is a husband, father, friend, retired Air Force pilot, Southwest pilot and recurrent L.A. County Lifeguard. Please help his family find a match. Adults age 18-44 can register for free and receive a cheek swab kit by mail. https://join.bethematch.org/curebrian
